<TEXT>
a usarmed guerrilla organization has 
reached tentative agreement with the sovietbacked government of 
angola on a plan to end 15 years of civil war rebel leader jonas 
savimbi said friday 
at a lengthy session thursday under the auspices of the united 
states soviet union and portugal the warring sides agreed to set 
a date for free elections and then immediately sign a ceasefire 
savimbi told reporters 
the breakthrough in the tortuous peace efforts followed a flurry 
of meetings here this week including an unprecedented session 
between savimbi and soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze 
savimbi who until now had been vilified by the kremlin as an 
anticommunist menace also met with president bush thursday 
in lisbon angolan foreign minister pedro de castro van dunem 
said a cease fire could be signed next month he spoke during a 
stopover on his return tom angola from a trip to washington 
washington and moscow have been pressing their allies in angola 
to stop the fighting which has killed over 300000 people and left 
the mineralrich country in ruin 
the united states has shipped unita as much as 50 million in 
weapons every year since 1986 the soviets have given the angolan 
government as much as 800 million annually us officials say 
under the proposed agreement reached thursday both sides would 
stop sending weapons once a ceasefire is signed us officials 
said 
savimbi said that at thursdays meeting the highestlevel 
gathering between the sides unita and the secondranking official 
in angolas ruling party lopo do nascimento had agreed on five 
points 
among them is agreement that signing of a ceasefire should be 
preceded by setting a date for free elections a ceasefire should 
be guaranteed by international observers and outside military 
assistance will stop once a ceasefire agreement is signed 
the other two points called for a democratic system of 
government and international monitoring of elections 
the sides agreed that international peacekeepers will be sent 
to angola under the banner of the united nations he said still to 
be settled he said are differences over the nations who will take 
part 
savimbi said all the participants except for the angolan 
government were ready to sign the fivepoint plan at thursdays 
session the angolan government official asked for more time to 
confer with his superiors in luanda savimbi said 
but he added there is no question that the government will 
agree in principle 
the us soviet and portuguese participants in the talks held a 
news conference late thursday saying significant progress was 
made but declined to elaborate at that time 
but a us official speaking on condition of anonymity on 
friday confirmed the gist of savimbis account of the meeting 
unita is optimistic that the remaining differences between the 
two parties can be successfully addressed and that signature of a 
ceasefire will be possible during the sixth round of 
negotiations he said 
the talks are scheduled next month in portugal the former 
colonial ruler of angola 
if the angolan government approves the five points and proposes 
a date for elections the sides can sign a ceasefire at the 
january session savimbi said elections could be held within nine 
months to a year from the ceasefire date he added 
if my party nominates me ill run for president savimbi 
said 
at the outset of the negotiations last year the government 
demanded that savimbi go into exile it later dropped that demand 
responding to military pressure from unita and to the democratic 
changes sweeping eastern europe the government also gradually 
moved away from a statecontrolled economy toward a market system 
last week angolas ruling party agreed to allow multiparty 
democracy and free elections 
