<TEXT>
defense secretary dick cheney has ordered the 
navy to justify the a12 attack plane in three weeks or else kill 
it because of intolerable problems the pentagon announced friday 
night 
if we cannot spend the taxpayers money wisely we will not 
spend it cheney said in a directive to navy secretary lawrence 
garrett 
the secretary gave the navy until jan 4 to justify the plane 
the announcement said a special team would meet with the 
contractors general dynamics corp and mcdonnell douglas corp 
both based in st louis to review the situation 
the a12 program is in serious trouble the apparent schedule 
slippage cost growth and management deficiences in this program 
are intolerable cheney said 
the a12 was supposed to replace the elderly a6 as the navys 
primary allweather carrierborne attack plane starting in 1995 
the plane was to use radarevading stealth techniques and carry 
the nickname avenger 
the navy had planned purchase of 620 planes for an estimated 52 
billion and deployment starting in 1995 
but a 47 billion development program supposed to deliver six 
prototypes is 1 billion over budget and 18 months behind 
schedule garrett recently ordered the admiral heading the program 
to retire and reassigned two other officers because the three 
failed to pass news of problems up the chain of command 
the navy has begun a criminal investigation of excessive 
payments to the contractors 
also john a betti the pentagons top procurement officer 
said wednesday he would resign as undersecretary of defense for 
acquisitions at the end of the year to avoid the bite of new ethics 
laws that take effect jan 1 officials said he had planned to 
leave anyway but the timing of his announcement was influenced by 
news of the a12s problems 
the departments inspector general said betti had failed to 
report conclusions of his own staff that the a12 was in trouble 
but had relied on assurances from the contractors and the navy that 
development would be completed under budget the contractors she 
said controlled the work of the governments inspectors 
garrett refused to block the promotion to rear admiral of one of 
the officers capt lawrence s elberfeld 
garrett defended the current procurement system but noted 
people find it very hard to push bad news up to the top 
large weapons purchases are not often cancelled many analysts 
have noted instead congress and the pentagon tend to look for 
ways to strech out production and buyj fewer models a tactic that 
frequently slows the production pace to inefficient rates and can 
even raise total costs if the a12 is cancelled it will be a 
rarity for such a large program 
cheney was particularly upset at being sandbagged by bad news 
with the a12 because he had reassured congress in april the plane 
was doing well five weeks before news of the cost overruns and 
delays became known at the time cheney announced a reduction in 
planned purchases from more than 800 to 620 
few details of the a12 or what has gone wrong with it have 
been released but stealth technology is brand new and known to be 
difficult an official sketch of the a12 shows a flyingwing 
design like the new air force b2 bomber another stealth plane 
that cost far more to develop than expected 
congress has committed funds to only 15 b2s and some estimates 
have reached 800 million a copy 
stealth techology much of it secret is known to involve novel 
shapes like the flying wing to deflect radar beams away rather than 
reflect them back to the antenna radarabsorbing materials on 
exterior surfaces and nonmetallic composites in the places 
structure that wont reflect radar 
the a6 called the intruder first flew in 1960 and early 
versions have long since been converted to tankers or other 
specialpurpose craft the last 10 airplanes of the series are 
being built by grumman corp under a contract calling for final 
delivery in september 1991 
still almost all carriers carry the a6 no other plane in the 
navy has the elaborate electronics that make possible attacks at 
night and in storms combined with the huge munitions load up to 
18000 pounds of the a6 
cheneys statement said that no matter what happens to the a12 
we will continue to need to develop a basic strike airplane for 
our aircraft carrier force the a6 our current carrier strike 
plane is aging and we must move ahead with an alternative that 
incorporates the technological advances necessary to maintain us 
naval air superiority 
older slower and less maneuverable a6 planes will be less 
able to penetrate enemy defenses and conduct their attacks stealth 
technology will be required if attack aircraft are to elude 
advanced fighters and surfacetoair missiles in the future the 
us needs to maintain the capability to project power through the 
use of naval strike forces cheney said 
a prominent congressional critic of the a12 rep john conyers 
dmich chairman of the house government operations committee 
said friday night he welcomed cheneys decision 
but the a12 is only the tip of the iceberg of the 
pentagons procurement problems conyers said 
a spokesman for chris schildz a spokesman for general dynamics 
said when asked for comment our representatives will be 
available to meet with government officials anytime jim reed 
spokesman for mcdonnell douglas said the company was hopeful 
that the current difficulties can be resolved quickly to everyones 
satisfaction we feel that the a12 program is very important for 
the defense of our country as well as to mcdonnell douglas 
</TEXT>
