<TEXT>
babies are twice as likely to die of sudden 
infant death syndrome in the winter than in the summer and at age 2 
months than age 4 months a new federal study shows 
ut even though sids experts long presumed those facts to be 
true they still dont know why 
the national centers for disease control analyzing eight years 
of infant mortality data reported thursday that the sids risk is 
twice as high in january as in july and more than twice as high at 
2 months as at 4 months 
the findings are important to researchers looking for the cause 
of sids which kills about 6000 american infants a year 
what we suspect is that an infectious process is somehow 
triggering death in these infants during cold weather said dr 
jose becerra an infant health specialist with the atlantabased 
cdc 
theres also a remarkably similar pattern for age and season 
in infectious diseases very similar he said its 
intriguing 
a 1988 study suggested a possible relationship between 
respiratory infections and sids pointing to episodes of vomiting 
or diarrhea in the two weeks preceding death in some cases 
that study indicated that breastfeeding could be protective 
against sids by guarding against gastrointestinal or respiratory 
infections 
breastfeeding might help avert some of the gastrointestinal 
illnesses which we know are more common in the winter months 
becerra said 
obviously if theres a correlation with respiratory 
infections or gi infections its patently reasonable that maybe 
the infection there is responsible said dr alfred 
steinschneider president of the atlantabased american sids 
institute 
we know babies who die of sids must have an underlying 
chronic abnormality he said respiratory infections or gi 
illnesses might act as a trigger to convert the predisposition to 
die into death 
nationwide the sids rate is 13 deaths for every 10000 live 
births according to cdc analyzing infant death statistics from 
1980 to 1987 the cdc also reported that sids rates were nearly 
twice as high for black babies as white babies and half again as 
high for baby boys as for baby girls 
the rate was highest for infants in the west and lowest in the 
northeast 
broken down by age sids rates were highest between 1 and 4 
completed months of life the sids risk peaks at 2 months 144 
percent higher or more than double the risk just two months 
later 
meanwhile sids risk peaked in december january and february 
the risk in july was 50 percent lower than that in january the 
highest month 
steinschneider stressed however that sids occurs all year 
often among premature or underweight babies 
what is important he said is a very practical thing get 
darned good prenatal care 
</TEXT>
