<DOCNO> AP901214-0022 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nuclear regulatory commission is 
reducing the amount of radiation to which workers at atomic plants 
and nearby residents may be exposed but critics contend the new 
ceilings already are outdated and inadequate 
the nrcs action on thursday represents the first broad 
revamping of radiation exposure limits for nuclear plant workers in 
33 years officials said it reflects new scientific findings on 
radiation risks 
radiation exposure to most atomic workers and people living near 
nuclear facilities already is well within the new requirements and 
few operational changes are expected said donald cool chief of 
the nrcs radiation protection and health effects branch 
the nrc has debated tighter controls on radiation exposure at 
nuclear facilities for a decade the final action comes 13 years 
after an international scientific advisory group recommended lower 
exposure ceilings levels identical to those required by the new 
rules 
under the new nrc requirements atomic plant workers may be 
exposed to no more than 5 rems of radiation per year and exposure 
to the general public may be no more than 100 millirems per year 
about onefifth of the current limit 
a rem which is the standard measure of radiation equals 1000 
millirems the nrc rules affect commercial nuclear power plants 
various laboratories and facilities involved in uranium production 
according to government studies people on average are exposed 
from normal background radiation and medical treatments to about 
360 millirems of radiation annually radiation from an xray is 
about 6 to 7 millirems 
the average exposure to plant workers is about 400 millirems a 
year and there has been no case reported where members of the 
general population have been exposed to levels anywhere near the 
new 100millirem ceiling said nrc spokesman joe fouchard 
critics however accused the nrc of not going far enough and of 
issuing new rules that will be outdated before they even go into 
effect beginning in 1993 
the nrcs lower radiation exposure levels reflect 
recommendations made as early as 1977 by the international 
commission on radiological protection a key scientific advisory 
body 
however the same group announced last summer that it considers 
its 1977 recommendations to be outdated the group is expected 
shortly to recommend maximum radiation exposure levels for atomic 
workers of 2 rems per year 
the lower ceiling is based on a number of recent studies on 
radiation health risks including one by the national academy of 
sciences earlier this year that put cancer risks from radiation two 
to five times greater than a similar study did in 1980 
the commission is straining its credibility by adopting an 
obsolete standard said michael mariotte executive director of 
the nuclear information and resource service an antinuclear 
umbrella group 
the nrc in explaining the regulatory change said the new 
requirements reflect changes in the basic philosophy of radiation 
protection and take into account recent scientific studies on the 
risks of radiation 
the commission said it didnt believe the imposition of even 
lower radiation exposure ceiling for nuclear workers is needed 
because actual contamination of most workers already is much lower 
than the 5remperyear standard being proposed 
in 1987 97 percent of all workers at nuclear plants and other 
atomic facilities were exposed to less than 2 rems of radiation 
annually the nrc said 
the new regulations also establish tighter standards that apply 
to pregnant workers at atomic facilities limiting exposure to 500 
millirems over the duration of the pregnancy and require that 
plants adopt formal policies to keep radiation doses as low as 
reasonably achievable 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

