<TEXT>
a longawaited study of the soviet economy is 
unlikely to recommend a flood of direct western assistance when it 
is released next week bush administration officials said 
rather they said the report will provide the most detailed 
analysis to date of the problems besetting the soviet economy and 
recommend ways in which technical assistance can be provided to the 
soviets 
a senior treasury department official speaking on condition his 
name not be used said thursday that the report should provide 
the most comprehensive and timely assessment that has been seen on 
the soviet economy 
but the official said he did not expect the document to support 
any push for large amounts of western aid until the soviets make 
greater strides toward a marketbased economy 
the report which is expected to be released dec 20 was 
ordered by president bush and the leaders of japan germany 
britain france italy and canada last july in houston during the 
annual economic summit meeting of the worlds seven largest 
industrial countries 
the study has been conducted by the international monetary fund 
and its sister lending organization the world bank along with the 
parisbased organization for economic cooperation and development 
and the european bank for reconstruction and development a lending 
agency created this year to promote economic development in eastern 
europe 
the study represented a way at the houston summit to reach a 
compromise between the demands of the french and germans for an 
immediate 15 billion western aid package and resistance to direct 
economic aid by bush and the other summit leaders 
bush announced wednesday that he was granting the soviet union 
up to 13 billion in federal loan guarantees for the purchase of 
american food and manufactured goods 
he also promised to provide emergency medical supplies to the 
soviets and dispatch a team of us experts to provide technical 
advice on ways to unclog the soviet food distribution system 
while bushs announcement represented the biggest package the 
administration has been willing to come up with so far it stopped 
far short of the hefty direct financial assistance that some 
european countries notably germany are providing to the soviets 
the 13 billion in credit guarantees is not a direct 
expenditure by the us government instead the government is 
promising to stand behind the loans that commercial banks make to 
the soviets to finance the purchase of american farm and 
manufactured products 
as part of the aid package bush also directed treasury 
secretary nicholas brady to present a proposal to the imf and the 
world bank to grant the soviets the status of a special 
associate at the two giant multinational lending institutions 
that designation falls far short of the full membership the 
soviets covet only full members of the imf and the world bank 
qualify for the billions of dollars in loans the two institutions 
make each year 
but the administration argued that the designation of special 
associate would serve as an important waystation for the soviets 
and did not preclude their admission as full members of the two 
organizations later 
in the meantime the initial ties with the imf and the world 
bank would allow the soviets to tap the considerable expertise the 
two agencies have in a variety of financial areas such as how to 
establish a stable currency system 
there is a tremendous experience and education gap and we hope 
this will fill that gap the treasury official said 
while the initial reaction among other western countries has 
been favorable to the us proposals the treasury official said 
more consultations would be necessary before putting the plan into 
operation 
but he indicated the details should be wrapped up fairly 
quickly possibly at an expected meeting in january of brady and 
finance ministers from the six other major industrialized 
countries 
