a strong earthquake shook a wide area of 
taiwan before dawn today hours after another quake on the island 
killed two people 
todays temblor caused power blackouts and landslides in the 
eastern city of hualien but there were no immediate reports of 
casualties 
the central weather bureau said todays quake struck at 349 
am and had a preliminary reading of 67 on the richter scale its 
epicenter was located in the pacific about 18 miles southeast of 
hualien 
more than 430 aftershocks hit the island including one at 718 
am with a reading of 57 on the richter scale the bureau said 
todays quake was felt in taipei 100 miles northwest of 
hualien it was the strongest to hit taiwan since november 1986 
when 13 people were killed by a tremor measuring 68 on the richter 
scale 
on thursday a tremor measuring 65 shook northeastern taiwan 
and more than 200 aftershocks were recorded the bureau reported 
two workers in hualien were killed in that quake 
residents were shaken awake by todays first tremor and many 
fled outdoors said lee laife a policeman in hualien 
several roads were blocked by landslides and power blackouts 
affected about 10000 households in the city lee said a fire 
caused by a short circuit in a power line destroyed three houses 
but injured no one 
police said a 12story building in downtown hualien was tilting 
and several other buildings showed cracks 
elementary and high schools in hualien were ordered closed today 
to allow authorities to check for possible structural damage 
officials said 
the richter scale measures ground motion as recorded on 
seismographs every increase of one unit represents a tenfold 
increase in intensity 
an earthquake with a magnitude of 6 can cause severe damage in a 
populated area while one of magnitude 7 is classified as a major 
earthquake capable of causing widespread heavy damage 
