<TEXT>
us charities are taking in more money this year than last but 
the needs of the poor are also rising and in the nations 
economically depressed northeast the organizations report giving 
has fallen off drastically 
charities across the country report increased demand for food 
shelter and clothing problems they blame on layoffs economic 
woes and government cutbacks 
its looking real scary said vicky wheeler of the central 
vermont community action council she said the number of daily 
visitors to the councils food bank is up from 15 to 35 in the past 
six months while donations have held steady the council has cut 
the size of its food packages by a third to make supplies last 
if we run out of food and cant help them theres not really 
any other place to turn she said 
other charities in the heavily industrialized northeast say 
contributions are down by as much as 67 percent from a year ago and 
their budgets are stretched pitifully thin 
nationally donations to the salvation army and goodwill 
industries of america inc are running about 8 percent above last 
years levels according to the national headquarters of those 
organizations 
two new yorkbased groups that keep tabs on charities the 
american association of fundraising council and the national 
charities information bureau also said the 1990 philanthropy 
tally is unlikely to fall below 1989s 115 billion 
giving for 1990 is expected to be up as it has been every 
year since 1955 said charities information bureau president ken 
albrecht 
but the united way of america which projects a 45 percent gain 
in contributions to local united way campaigns said collection 
levels fluctuate widely from region to region 
if you want to talk about new england were down there a 
couple percentage points if you want to talk about the pacific 
northwest seattle is up in the double digits said richard 
fusco united way vice president for resource development 
of 80 local organizations contacted by the associated press 54 
said donations were flat or below yearago levels and 49 reported 
increased demand for their services 
fourteen said they stepped up their efforts this year because 
they expected hard times and 12 said they either had cut budgets 
and staff or were considering doing so 
