laboratory said he is optimistic engineers can repeatedly use the 
spacecrafts thrusters to minimize the wobble when ulysses becomes 
the first spacecraft to orbit the suns poles during 1994 and 1995 
i dont foresee that anybody here or in europe is going to 
write off this mission as a failure said ed smith nasas chief 
scientist for ulysses its a question of how much of the cake 
you want to have 
if corrective maneuvering is successful ulysses would lose only 
20 percent of the information it was designed to collect but if it 
fails we would stand to lose 90 percent of the data said 
edgar page ulysses science coordinator for the european space 
agency 
smith was less pessimistic than page saying that at worst 
ulysses would be unable to transmit 70 percent to 75 percent of the 
information it was designed to collect 
the wobble threatens the mission because it makes it difficult 
for ulysses to keep its main dishshaped antenna pointed at earth 
to transmit the information it collects 
the malfunctioning spacecraft is the latest headache for the 
national aeronautics and space administration which has been 
bedeviled by space shuttle fuel leaks trouble with the hubble 
space telescope and major glitches with an observatory that flew 
aboard shuttle columbia this month 
ulysses is a joint mission of the european space agency which 
supplied the spacecraft and half its science instruments and nasa 
which built the remaining instruments launched the spacecraft and 
is tracking it the mission cost is 750 million including 250 
million for the spacecraft 
ulysses is now flying toward jupiter the planets gravity will 
act like a slingshot in 1992 to hurl ulysses out of the plane in 
which the planets orbit the sun ulysses then will fly over the 
suns polar regions in 1994 and 1995 
the slow wobble unexpectedly developed nov 4 when ulysses 
extended a 24footlong antenna boom which is different than the 
main antenna the boom was designed to study radio signals and 
solar wind waves 
we arent sure why its happening page said 
meeks said the leading theory is that heat from the sun is 
warming one side of the boom while the other side remains cool 
causing the boom to bend the boom then makes the entire spacecraft 
wobble like an offbalance washing machine when it spins it was 
designed to spin to prevent wobbling 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

