official of hobby japan co the distributor 
he said the company also has halted plans to produce a 
japaneselanguage version of the roleplaying game which is based 
on feudal japanese society 
although less than 200 copies of the game were sold in japan at 
a list price of 35 the distributor moved quickly to withdraw it 
after it was criticized by the buraku liberation league 
the league which claims 200000 members has fought 
discrimination faced by burakumin a former outcast group estimated 
to number between 1 million and 3 million out of japans total 
population of 123 million 
hundreds of years ago the burakumin or village people worked 
in religiously proscribed occupations such as butchering and 
leather working they lived in special neighborhoods or buraku 
and when maps were drawn the buraku were omitted 
although racially identical to other japanese the burakumin 
continue to face difficulties in employment and marriage more than 
100 years after their outcast status was officially abolished in 
1871 
japans family registry system allows people to be traced to 
their ancestral communities although public access to the 
registries has been limited in recent years 
we definitely feel there are serious problems with the game 
a league official said 
the league said it plans to send a delegation to the united 
states to meet with the maker of the game baltimorebased avalon 
hill game co 
in the game players make a journey after being assigned roles 
such as samurai warrior ninja or buddhist priest the manual 
describes feudal japan by dividing all occupations into four 
descending hierarchical groups nobles samurai commoners and 
eta 
the latter term a derogatory name for burakumin meaning great 
filth is defined in the game as those outside normal society 
such as ninja thieves and entertainers 
the game introduced in 1987 also refers to native ainu people 
another minority as barbarian inhabitants of northern japan 
