<TEXT>
industrial production plunged 17 percent in 
november its steepest drop since the last recession the federal 
reserve said friday many analysts expressed concern over the 
quickness and severity of the slump in the manufacturing sector 
all notions that the economy might skirt a recession are 
dashed by the report said william k macreynolds an economist 
with the us chamber of commerce clearly the economy rapidly is 
falling to a degree not anticipated by most analysts just two short 
months ago 
its pretty clear that the weakness in the last couple of 
months has been pretty severe added economist robert brusca of 
nikko securities co international in new york if this isnt 
what a recession is i dont know what one is 
the fed said the drop was the steepest since output sank 20 
percent in december 1982 as the nation began crawling out of the 
last recession 
the decline began with a 01 percent tumble in september 
followed by a 09 percent fall in october both months were revised 
downward from a positive 02 percent in september and a negative 
08 percent in october 
the dramatic declines indicate the manufacturing sector is 
suffering along with the rest of the economy as the business cycle 
takes a turn for the worse said economist mark m zandi of 
regional financial associates in west chester pa 
but zandi and others while acknowledging the bleak 
industrial production report found some hope in fridays commerce 
department report that business inventories grew a modest 04 
percent in october while sales expanded 09 percent 
that resulted in an inventorytosales ratio of 147 down from 
148 the previous month the ratio means it would take 147 months 
to exhaust the backlog of goods at the october sales pace the 
ratio reached a 174 in january 1982 during the last recession 
the fact that inventories remained lean suggests that although 
were in a slowdown theres not a lot of inventory correction 
needed and that will keep the slowdown mild and of shorter 
duration he said 
evelina tainer an economist with first national bank of 
chicago said the ratio suggests unemployment will go up but not 
as much as in past recessions major inventory accumulations 
could cause growing production cutbacks and even larger job layoffs 
as businesses attempt to sell off the backlog 
nevertheless the labor department still reported that 200000 
factory jobs were lost in november the biggest onemonth drop 
since 1982 since reaching a postrecession peak in january 1989 
manufacturing employment has declined by 800000 
a 20 percent drop in motor vehicle assemblies coupled with a 
sharp curtailment in output of related parts and materials 
accounted for more than half of the overall loss in industrial 
output the fed said but all categories posted declines 
production at manufacturing plants making both durable and 
nondurable goods also plummeted 17 percent for its third 
consecutive drop 
output of durable goods usually expensive products expected to 
last more than three years sank 25 percent after a 11 percent 
drop in october 
manufacturing of nondurable goods which has been declining 
since july dropped 06 percent after 04 percent drops in both 
september and october 
utility production fell 36 percent its third straight decline 
while output at mines inched down 01 percent after a 10 percent 
drop in october 
the fed said its industrial production index in november stood 
at 1075 percent of its 1987 base down from 1094 percent a month 
earlier it matched the level of last january which was the lowest 
since the index stood at 1074 percent in december 1988 
the fed also said the operating rate of the nations factories 
mines and utilities dropped 15 percentage point to 809 percent of 
capacity the operating rate measures not only output but also 
changes in productivity levels 
the operating rate at factories was 800 percent down from 816 
percent in october the operating rate at mines was unchanged at 
896 percent for utilities it fell to 827 percent from 859 
percent a month earlier 
