<TEXT>
mourners remembered human rights activist andrei 
d sakharov on friday a year after his death as an extraordinary 
moral force whose place in politics and in their hearts has yet to 
be matched by anyone else 
i cant see anybody now whose ideas i could agree with he was 
a man whose thoughts could find a response in peoples souls 
said bela kleshchenko an activist standing beside sakharovs grave 
at a snowy cemetery in southwest moscow 
i cant see anybody today who could take his place said 
67yearold pensioner baruch froyimovich tearyeyed as he looked 
at the grave you need a man who has very high culture heart 
soul and brains he was man of the highest culture 
sakharov was a top soviet physicist who helped develop the 
hydrogen bomb in the 1950s and later won the 1975 nobel peace prize 
for his campaigns on behalf of disarmament and human rights 
he died a year ago at age 68 after three vigorous years of 
political activism following his emergence from forced internal 
exile 
controversial for much of his political life sakharov has 
gained steadily in public esteem since his death groups scramble 
to attach his name to their cause and his words are quoted by 
politicians and commentators alike as the country deals with 
worsening political and economic crises 
in 1980 sakharov was denounced in the official press as an 
utterly ignorant person and exiled to the closed city of gorky 
for criticizing the soviet invasion of afghanistan 
president mikhail s gorbachev released him in december 1986 
and he returned to moscow where he became an outspoken deputy in 
the supreme soviet parliament 
russian federation president boris yeltsin opened fridays 
session of the russian parliament with a tribute to sakharov and 
national newspapers published articles praising him 
the government plans to make a museum out of his old apartment 
in gorky which has since been renamed nizhninovgorod 
but at the cemetery ms kleshchenko said politicians were 
cashing in on sakharovs name without fulfilling his ideals 
the powers that be brought about his death and now they 
are preparing to establish a museum in his honor said ms 
kleshchenko a member of the sakharov order of charity and social 
defense 
our politicians are too busy with politics and they dont 
really have any human qualities she said what was so special 
about sakharov was that he was a scholar a politician and a man 
he was still human 
at the huge cemetery the rumble of trucks on a nearby highway 
was barely audible next to sakharovs grave which was covered by a 
blanket of evergreen twigs and carnations of all colors 
a blackandwhite portrait of the physicist hung from the 
headstone flanked by evergreen wreaths that bore sashes from the 
russian parliament and democratic activists a halfdozen candles 
flickered in the subfreezing breeze in front of the grave 
pairs of policemen stood at each corner of a path leading to the 
gravesite apparently on guard in case of any demonstrations but 
the mood was solemn and people spoke softly or not at all 
at the parliament sergei kovalev a deputy and close friend 
said sakharov was intrepid and unselfish in the quest of truth 
he was always outside the turmoil of political passions and 
ambitions he took interest in nothing but the truth 
the moscow newspaper leninskoye znamiya said history has 
already had its say on sakharov he belongs to it at the same 
time he is near us he stayed in the hearts of all who wanted to 
have him 
