<TEXT>
philadelphia missed a selfimposed deadline 
friday for solving its cash crunch but the city treasurer said he 
expected a deal to be ready by next week 
several parties interested in lending money have declined to 
commit themselves pending resolution of such issues as fiscal 
reform and who gets repaid first city treasurer benjamin blakney 
said 
the city intends to sell about 300 million in shortterm notes 
to banks two pension boards and the investment firm merrill lynch 
to avoid going broke before major tax payments come due in february 
and march 
a 375 million note issue collapsed in september amid worries 
about the citys fiscal condition bondrating agencies have 
dropped philadelphias credit rating this year to junkbond levels 
the lowest among major us cities 
unless it receives a cash infusion the city has warned it will 
not be able to meet payroll as early as dec 28 for city workers 
finance director elizabeth c reveal in a letter monday set 
deadlines of friday for commitments to buy notes and next wednesday 
for closing the deal 
there are open issues which clearly are still being looked at 
and quite frankly are still being discussed blakney said we 
will continue as expeditiously as possible to resolve those 
issues 
he said interest rates were less of a stumbling block than 
structural aspects of the transaction while declining to go into 
details he said major unresolved issues included fiscal reform and 
whether all note holders would be repaid simultaneously 
representatives from a consortium of banks met privately with 
gov robert p casey on thursday and mayor w wilson goode on 
riday the banks reportedly have sought a fiscal control board 
doubledigit interest rates and assurances they would be repaid 
before other note buyers 
goode described his meeting with the bankers as very 
constructive said his press secretary karen warrington 
the mayor feels theyre continuing to make progress and the 
parties are working to pull together a package that could avoid a 
missed payroll she said 
members of the city pension board and the state teachers pension 
fund met but did not vote on any proposals related to the note 
sale 
the city board of pensions and retirement is awaiting a report 
from ian lanoff a washington pensionlaw expert who was hired to 
advise them on the note transaction 
blakney said lanoff was finetuning some of the salient 
details of a response to the citys proposal 
similar responses were being drafted by the banks merrill lynch 
and consultants to the state public school employees retirement 
board he said 
goode and other democratic leaders have urged higher taxes 
spending cuts longterm deficit financing and other steps to stem 
the red ink action on those steps is not expected until the state 
legislature reconvenes early next year 
