myrlie evers the widow of slain civil 
rights leader medgar evers testified for an hour friday before a 
grand jury investigating her husbands 1963 assassination 
im filled with a little apprehension a lot of hope and 
faith evers said as she left the hinds county courthouse where 
the grand jury met amid speculation it may issue a new indictment 
in the 27yearold case 
the panel thursday summoned a former police detective who 
investigated the slaying scene at evers jackson home grand jurors 
also examined the rifle used to kill evers 
byron de la beckwith 70 a white supremacist from signal 
mountain tenn has said he is the target of the grand jury 
investigation he has also said he is innocent 
beckwith was arrested after the slaying but two 1964 trials 
ended with allwhite juries deadlocked on verdicts the original 
murder indictment was dismissed in 1969 
beckwith was a greenwood fertilizer salesman at the time of the 
slaying evers 37 when he died was field secretary for the 
mississippi branch of the national association for the advancement 
of colored people 
assistant district attorney bobby delaughter spent nearly six 
hours with the grand jury thursday 
delaughter who has spent 14 months looking into the slaying 
couldnt comment on the secret proceedings but he did say he views 
reopening the case as a way to help right an old wrong 
this single cowardly act of the person responsible for medgar 
evers assassination has probably done more to hurt the state and 
to hurt the perception of mississippi and mississippians across the 
nation and possibly the world than any other single act i can 
think of delaughter said 
if its possible to right that wrong i certainly think we 
have a responsibility of doing that if we could pick up where the 
previous investigation left off produce more evidence i think we 
have an obligation of doing that delaughter said 
state fire marshal john chamblee a jackson police detective 
sergeant at the time of the june 12 1963 slaying would not 
comment thursday after leaving the grand jury room 
one piece of evidence seen taken into the grand jury room was a 
1917 model 3006 enfield rifle equipped with a scope 
at the two 1964 trials a jackson police fingerprint expert 
testified prints found on the scope matched beckwiths 
testimony in the trials also showed beckwith obtained the rifle 
in 1960 and acquired the scope about one month before evers was 
shot beckwith testified that the rifle was stolen from him 
evers 57yearold widow now a los angeles public works 
commissioner spent most of thursday in the district attorneys 
office at the courthouse 
im here to assist in any way i possibly can with the grand 
jury hearing she said its something that needs to be put to 
rest justice needs to be done for the state of mississippi and for 
medgars family im hopeful this time 
