<TEXT>
president bush seeking to avoid a damaging 
civil rights dispute said friday he has asked his staff to get a 
quick readout on an education department ruling that could bar 
colleges from directing scholarship funds to minorities 
were looking at it right now bush said at a news 
conference when asked about the surprise decision which drew an 
immediate outcry from civil rights and education leaders 
the education departments assistant secretary for civil rights 
michael l williams on wednesday announced that it was illegal for 
federally supported institutions to offer scholarships specifically 
for minorities 
he cited title vi of the 1964 civil rights act which prohibits 
discrimination on the ground of race color or national origin in 
any program or activity receiving federal financial assistance 
the white house acknowledged friday that it was caught offguard 
by the decision presidential press secretary marlin fitzwater said 
that while bush supports affirmative action programs for 
minorities he is against quota systems 
this is a kind of an inbetween case that is not clear exactly 
where it comes through how it would be applied what it means 
fitzwater said 
bush defended williams saying he was an extrardinarily 
sensitive person i dont think anyone would accuse him of doing it 
on a racist basis 
williams 37 is a black lawyer who prosecuted racial crimes in 
the reagan administrations justice department and served as deputy 
assistant secretary for law enforcement in the treasury department 
before moving to education 
williams on friday told louisville civil rights activist rev 
louis coleman that the issue of racespecific scholarships was 
still under discussion coleman told the associated press 
coleman quoted williams as saying the issue was now in other 
hands suggesting that higher officials in the bush 
administration had moved in to prevent a further widening of the 
rift between bush and civil rights groups 
bush this fall vetoed a major civil rights bill passed by 
congress on the grounds it would create quota systems in the 
employment of minorities civil rights groups said the veto showed 
the administrations insensitivity to minority problems 
on friday civil rights leaders jesse jackson said the education 
departments premise that minority scholarships are illegal because 
we now live in a colorblind society is patently false and 
morally reprehensible 
he said the president has the power to overrule williams and 
we must write and telephone president bush and register our 
protest and outrage 
also on friday deputy secretary of education ted sanders met 
the leaders of six national educational associations to assure them 
that scholarships already granted to minority students will not be 
affected 
sanders said the department hopes to issue a clarification on 
the issue in the next few weeks department spokesman john bertak 
said 
educators say they are not clear what programs or how many 
people could be affected by the ruling federally funded programs 
to assist minorities are apparently not involved and private grants 
are permissible targeted would be college and university programs 
that set aside funding specifically for certain minorities 
