<TEXT>
a detonator fragment from the bomb that brought 
down pan am flight 103 links libya to the 1988 attack that killed 
270 people a newspaper reported friday 
the report quoted unidentified senior sources as saying 
indictments have been held up because any us action against libya 
would risk alienating arab members of the multinational force 
against iraq in the persian gulf 
in its report the independent said the evidence came to light 
three months ago and is based on a detonator fragment found in a 
field close to the southern scottish town of lockerbie the plane 
blew up over that town 
the fragment matched a detonator found in a radiocassette bomb 
seized from two libyan agents at dakar airport in senegal in 
february 1988 10 months before the flight 103 attack the 
newspaper reported the two men were later released by senegalese 
authorities 
investigators have said the bomb that exploded on the pan am 
plane was also hidden in a radiocassette recorder 
reports of possible libyan involvement have appeared recently in 
the french and us media but the paper said it is the first time 
that senior sources confirmed that proof exists implicating col 
moammar gadhafis regime 
it quoted one of the sources as saying not only do we now 
know gadhafi was responsible he also knows we know 
some previous reports speculated the bombing was planned by a 
germanbased cell of the radical syriabased popular front for the 
liberation of palestinegeneral command headed by ahmed jibril 
the bomb was reportedly made with semtex a czechoslovak explosive 
terrorist experts and western news reports have theorized that 
jibrils organization was hired by iran to avenge the deaths of 290 
people aboard an iran air jetliner accidentally shot down by the 
us navy in july 1988 
