<TEXT>
the official newspaper china daily acknowledging 
the importance of private enterprise said friday that china plans 
to increase the number of its free markets by more than 10 percent 
in the next five years 
the announcement reflects a shift in public pronouncements since 
last year when private vendors came under strong criticism the 
economy remains largely controlled by the communist government 
however china daily noted friday a growing reliance on free 
markets which chiefly sell food clothing and furniture it said 
the number of free markets will increase by more than 10 percent by 
1995 
the newspaper said unofficial statistics show chinas urban 
residents now buy 60 percent to 70 percent of their vegetables and 
nonstaple food from free markets farmers sell about half their 
products at the markets it said 
chinese buy staple foods at staterun stores where they use 
ration coupons that let them make purchases at a discount they 
turn to free markets to supplement food supplies and buy items 
unavailable from state outlets 
since free markets reappeared in china 11 years ago they have 
been playing an increasingly important role in the daily lives of 
urban and rural residents china daily said 
after the governments violent crackdown on the prodemocracy 
movement in june 1989 private enterprises were targets in 
wideranging attacks on capitalism staterun media carried reports 
rebuking private businessmen accusing them of making too much 
money and of tax evasion 
official regulations still prohibit the free markets from 
selling most raw materials and many consumer items including 
tobacco liquor and cotton 
