<TEXT>
soviet defense spending fell by 4 
percent in 1989 and will continue to drop in real terms until at 
least 1995 the north atlantic treaty organization reported friday 
the report was the first authoritative sign that the eastwest 
thaw has led to reduced soviet military spending earlier natos 
military leaders said they noticed no appreciable decline 
fridays report put soviet 1989 defense outlays at between 244 
billion and 266 billion according to moscows official exchange 
rate 
that would be double a figure cited by soviet president mikhail 
s gorbachev in may 1989 however it is hard to reflect soviet 
defense spending in western money because the ruble is not 
convertible to other currencies and the price the kremlin pays for 
arms is well below actual production costs 
unilateral force reductions withdrawals from eastern europe 
and cuts in military production led to a 4 percent real decline in 
expenditure in 1989 nato said in an annual survey of soviet 
defense spending 
it predicted a similar drop in 1990 adding that the soviet 
defense budget is likely to decline in real terms until at least 
1995 due to the end of the cold war 
in 1989 moscow spent up to 17 percent of its gross domestic 
product on defense the report said it said the nato allies spend 
an average of 44 percent for defense 
the 16 nato allies spent an aggregate total of about 470 
billion on defense in 1989 
the nato report said the rate of decrease in soviet defense 
spending hinges on further arms control accords a possible breakup 
of the soviet union and economic reforms notably efforts to 
convert military production to civilian output 
in the 1990s nato said it expected the soviets to embark on a 
radical reduction in the size of the militaryindustrial complex 
and a further shifting of resources to the civilian sector 
</TEXT>
