<TEXT>
when the stock market script for 1991 starts to 
play out in a couple of weeks one familiar element will be missing 
narration by monte gordon 
the 67yearold gordon one of wall streets most widely quoted 
analysts on the ups and downs of the world of finance retires dec 
31 after 18 years as research director at the moneymanagement firm 
of dreyfus corp 
gordons bespectacled face became a fixture in television 
coverage of the stock market all through the turbulent 1980s 
long before that he was well known to newspaper reporters and 
many of their readers as an everavailable source of market 
information and analysis often served up in a style that might be 
called unabashed baroque 
a vintage gordonism delivered on what others might have thought 
of as just a dull day on wall street the market is languishing 
in the shadow of its own worries 
over a career of more than four decades he previously worked 
at what is now prudentialbache securities gordon says he has 
kept an abiding fascination with the financial markets 
its always exhilarating and never the same from one day to 
the next he told a visitor to his 55thfloor office in 
midmanhattan you never lose the zest for this 
asked how his job has changed over time gordon immediately 
pointed to todays instant communications systems embodied by 
computer screens with instantbyinstant charts of market activity 
there was a time when if you wanted to know what was going on 
you had to call a broker on the floor of the exchange he said 
all that has changed with the structure of the flow of 
information 
given shortened reaction times in what has become a worldwide 
business and the development of such techniques as 
computerprogram trading is the market more volatile now than it 
used to be 
it has more potential for volatility its like a coiled 
spring gordon observed but the basic verities of what is a 
good stock what is a good company havent changed 
a dark moment in recent wall street history the crash of 1987 
provided a high spot in gordons memory of his years of market 
forecasting right after the break i said buy em going on 
experience and instinct he recalls that was fun 
after the 80s which he describes as a time of great 
innovation and vitality gordon acknowledges that stocks and wall 
street are now paying part of the price for past euphoria 
while that may continue for a while he says eventually the 
stock market of the 90s is going to be strong different from 
the 80s but strong 
for the typical individual investor in late 1990 he recommends 
committing about 60 percent of assets to stockrelated investments 
30 percent to bonds and 10 percent to moneymarket vehicles he 
doesnt counsel waiting for the economic outlook to clear before 
putting the money to work 
remember he says we started the 80s with the recession 
of 198182 if you wait for somebody to ring a bell or blow a 
whistle before you invest its too late 
after years of being consulted and scrutinized by reporters he 
was asked how does he appraise the way broadcasters and the press 
cover the markets 
the coverage is better now much more knowledgeable and much 
more detailed he says theres a tendency toward hype 
overdramatizing whats going on but the quality and extent of the 
coverage is much improved 
