sales of north americanmade cars and light 
trucks jumped 223 percent earlier this month but analysts say the 
rise doesnt reflect the actual weakness in the auto market 
deteriorating confidence in the economy is producing a 
selfperpetuating downward cycle said senior economist tom webb 
of the national automobile dealers association in mclean va 
the 10 major automakers building cars and trucks in north 
america said thursday their vehicles sold at an average daily rate 
of 27624 during the dec 110 period compared with a rate of 
22589 during the same time last year 
car sales were up 278 percent and truck sales rose 143 percent 
during the period compared with a year ago which was the weakest 
selling period of 1989 
sales of domestically made cars by general motors corp ford 
motor co and chrysler corp rose 293 percent compared with 
yearago levels while sales of north american built cars with 
japanese company nameplates increased 142 percent 
the big three held 91 percent of the domestic car market 
the seemingly large increase didnt impress auto analyst mary 
anne sudol of fitch investors service inc in new york 
the news out of motown is not too terrific she said 
consumers are putting rubber bands over their wallets and cutting 
up their plastic credit cards 
a more accurate picture emerges from the sales rate for the 
entire year sales of north americanmade cars and trucks between 
jan 1 and dec 10 this year were running 31 percent behind last 
year with car sales down 31 percent and truck sales off 33 
percent 
the auto industry which has slipped into a recession watched 
its total sales plunge in november when fleet orders which had 
inflated october sales numbers dried up 
the comparisons are against a disastrous yearago period 
webb said true demand absent the artificial prop of fleet 
deals remains weak and our normally upbeat dealers are becoming 
almost as pessimistic as consumers 
