grain and soybean futures prices closed slightly 
higher friday in lackluster trading on the chicago board of trade 
the market was in a bearish position as a result of the 
smallerthanexpected us export credits given the soviet union 
earlier this week analysts said 
traders were wary of taking positions pending an announcement 
of a breakdown of the commodities the soviet union will buy with 
the 500 million to 1 billion in export credits said analyst joel 
karlin of research department inc 
corn futures came under pressure with news that south korea made 
a major purchase of chinese corn 
wheat futures were boosted by a decision of the us agriculture 
department to allow producers to place up to 300 million bushels of 
wheat in the farmerowned reserve the decision was made because of 
concern over falling prices and lagging exports 
at the close wheat was 1 cents lower cent higher with the 
contract for delivery in december at 253 a bushel corn was 
cent lower to 1 higher with december at 223 a bushel oats were 
cent to 1 cent higher with december at 108 a bushel soybeans 
were cent to 1 cents higher with january at 588 a bushel 
