<TEXT>
tribune co said friday its operating profit 
will slide substantially more than 25 percent this year because of 
the weak advertising climate and rising costs of a strike at its 
new york daily news 
company executives failed to specify how much the sevenweekold 
strike by nine of the 10 labor unions at the newspaper is costing 
the paper has continued to publish despite the strike although 
circulation is down sharply 
the executives repeated earlier assertions that they intended to 
continue publishing the paper as long as it continues to progress 
in a separate appearance before securities analysts at the 
annual painewebber media outlook conference knightridder inc 
said it expected earnings would be up modestly in 1990 compared 
with results in 1989 that excluded a gain on the sale of a 
newspaper 
chairman james batten said the miamibased newspaper and 
information services company has a realistic chance for at least 
a flat year in earnings per share next year 
the companies made their appearances on the closing day of the 
weeklong conference that has featured mostly glum earnings 
forecasts due to advertising demand that has weakened along with 
the economy 
a top advertising forecaster robert coen has estimated ad 
spending will rise only 49 percent this year its slowest pace of 
growth since 1975 and grow 46 percent in 1991 
tribune which publishes the chicago tribune and five other 
newspapers in addition to the news and owns six television 
stations earned 317 a share for all of 1989 operating earnings 
amounted to 433 million last year 
but the tough advertising climate helped push operating earnings 
for the first nine months of this year down 25 percent from a year 
ago as a doubledigit decline in the newspaper group more than 
offset gains in broadcasting and entertainment operations 
fourthquarter earnings while not out yet also are below 
levels of last year the news employees went on strike on oct 25 
and newsprint operations were depressed by a strike at canadian 
mill that has just been resolved 
scott smith chief financial officer of the tribune said 
operating results are down by about 20 percent in the last three 
months of the year excluding the effect of the strikes and 
substantially more if they are included 
he said the decline in operating profit for the full year will 
be substantially larger than 25 percent including strike costs 
smith told analysts that earnings per share excluding losses at 
the daily news and the newsprint mill should amount to about 3 
compared with 317 a year ago and said earnings will be below 3 
a share next year 
he said the company would disclose the magnitude of the losses 
at the daily news when it reports its 1990 earnings early next 
year 
daily news publisher james hoge said the newspaper continues to 
hope a reasonable settlement can be reached to end the strike but 
that the paper will continue to publish as long as it was making 
progress toward regaining circulation and advertising 
he said daily circulation has reached about 600000 after 
sinking as low as 250000 shortly after the strike began it was 
more than 109 million before the strike 
hoge has previously said the daily news lost 115 million 
betwen 1979 and 1989 and that losses by the end of 1990 will rise 
to about 200 million 
financial analysts who were the only attendees allowed to ask 
questions at the session did not ask about the size of the news 
losses 
knightridder which owns 29 daily newspapers including the 
miami herald and the phildelphia inquirer said it anticipates 
earning 290 to 297 a share in 1990 compared with 286 a share 
excluding a gain on the sale of a newspaper in 1989 
the advertising climate has weakend along with the economy in 
the fourth quarter but knightridder aides said earnings per share 
should at least match the 1990 figure in 1991 
revenue is expected to rise 2 percent to 3 percent next year 
with slightly higher revenue from newspapers and a doubledigit 
increase from business information services said robert singleton 
senior vice president for finance 
</TEXT>
