<DOCNO> AP901214-0243 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
union workers overwhelming approved a 
new contract friday with delta pride catfish inc ending a bitter 
threemonth strike that brought out allegations of racial 
discrimination 
the plight of the workers in one of the nations most 
economically depressed regions attracted support from the naacp and 
other civil rights organizations and led to a national boycott of 
delta pride products 
the contract vote was 4791 union officials said the lone vote 
against appeared to be a misunderstanding over wage provisions in 
the pact 
this is a great christmas present said sarah white a shop 
steward who has been with delta pride since 1983 one year after 
the nations largest catfish processor opened i feel good about 
this contract and ive talked with several coworkers and they are 
satisfied 
we finally got some of the things we wanted including 
things that should make the workplace better for all of us 
the strike began sept 13 when members of united food and 
commercial workers union local 1529 rejected a contract about 900 
workers walked off the job at delta prides indianola and inverness 
plants a third plant in belzoni employs nonunion workers 
the company had no immediate comment on the contract vote 
provisions in the contract include wage increases and assurances 
that striking workers will be rehired union officials said 
the contract grants immediate raises of 60 to 65 cents an hour 
for all workers with at least one year of seniority pay averaged 
405 an hour before the strike the pact also establishes a 
workermanagement health and safety committee to monitor conditions 
at the plant 
while there were scattered reports of violence including 
rockthrowing early in the strike officials said recent weeks 
were quiet 
aaron henry president of the mississippi naacp said the 
workers anger arose from a combination of race and economics 
coupled with the philosophy of the plantation 
besides wages the union also raised concerns about working 
conditions a common complaint among workers has been about 
repetitive motion injury 
workers complained that they were timed with a stopwatch when 
skinning gutting slicing and packaging fish the also complained 
of limited restroom breaks six fiveminute bathroom breaks per 
week violators risked dismissal 
white who has two children said the three months she has been 
on strike created financial problems but the union helped take 
care of our bills and provided groceries for us we really 
sacrificed but we had help with the basics 
white 32 of moorhead said she planned to be in st louis this 
weekend to attend a support rally for the striking workers 
now i can tell them it is over and tell them to start buying 
catfish we need the hours at work she said 
e dale cline of memphis tenn the federal mediator who helped 
work out the new contract said he is tickled to death that this 
is finally over 
union spokesman neel lattimore said the contract goes a long way 
toward improving working conditions 
we feel like there is language in the contract to make delta 
pride more sensitive to working conditions and by all of us 
working together we can get along he said 
</TEXT>
