<TEXT>
for weeks the nations farmers and grain and soybean traders had 
been waiting with anticipation the bush administrations decision 
on extending export credits to the soviet union 
that decision came wednesday and it was disappointing 
the united states will grant 500 million to 1 billion in 
export credits to the soviet union to buy much needed grain and 
other food products 
traders were expecting a credit package of 15 billion remarks 
by sen robert dole rkan led the markets to believe the 
administration could grant the soviets 3 billion in credits 
farmers and traders were pressing for the granting of export 
credits to the soviets because us exports have been lagging 
tremendously 
this year corn exports are 36 percent behind levels last year 
wheat shipments are down 23 percent and soybean exports are at 
their lowest levels in 16 years 
our exports are so far behind if we dont start giving stuff 
away we are going to end up with excess inventory said william 
biedermann an analyst with allendale inc in chicago 
but analysts said credits of less than 1 billion wont allow 
the soviet union improve this countrys grain exports they wont 
allow the soviets to fulfill their longterm grainbuying agreement 
with the united states the soviets are committed to buy 12 
million metric tons of wheat and 600000 metric tons of corn by 
yearend 
the apparent lack of generosity by the united states has riled 
some traders 
analyst daniel basse of agresource co in chicago said the 
amount of the credits are equivalent to a miniembargo he says 
that since other nations are offering the soviets as much as 12 
billion in food aid theres some pretty intense competition for 
their business 
other grainexporting nations have freely given export credits 
to the soviets which put pressure on the us to extend export 
credits bumper crops have given the soviets access to soybean meal 
and corn from south america and wheat for europe and canada 
disappointment with the smallerthanexpected offering of export 
credits extended to the livestock and pork market 
a larger credit line had been expected to lead to meat purchases 
by the soviets but they are now likely to confine purchases to 
grains 
beidermann said farmers particularly those who do not 
participate in government programs have been hard hit by the 
declining exports he said there is no reason for the united states 
to be reluctant to sell its grain to the soviets because the nation 
has so much 
in granting the credits president bush lifted a 15year ban 
imposed because of the soviet prohibition of free emigration the 
jacksonvanik amendment barred closer ussoviet economic ties 
until soviet jews and others were free to emigrate in large 
numbers 
this year 150000 soviet jews have moved to israel and 50000 
to the united states kremlin officials said this past week that a 
further liberalization in immigration laws was planned 
