<TEXT>
wall street analysts have some words of caution 
for all investors consumers and business planners who have put 
lower interest rates on their holidayseason wish lists this 
year 
true interest rates have come down significantly since they hit 
their 1990 peaks around the beginning of autumn 
true also the federal reserve seems committed to a policy of 
gradually but steadily loosening its credit policy helping to 
foster lower rates as it seeks to cushion the impact of a 
developing recession 
and true too the consensus prediction among financial analysts 
is for further declines in interest rates at least through the 
early stages of 1991 
but at least a few scroogian voices can be heard in the chorus 
of yearend forecasts being issued these days in the investment 
world 
quite a few potential pitfalls dot the road to lower rates this 
winter the skeptics say furthermore they add even if rates are 
indeed headed for further declines the circumstances that permit 
that to happen may be pretty unpleasant 
one widely cited prerequisite for lower rates is a steady 
improvement in the news on inflation wall street suffered a 
disappointment on that score friday when the labor department 
reported that the producer price index rose 05 percent in 
november 
traders had been expecting a considerably smaller increase 
given a recent letup in the rise of oil prices 
the inflation outlook could be scrambled further should the 
showdown in the persian gulf take an unexpected turn sending oil 
higher once again 
the gulf crisis and oil prices are the obvious wild cards 
observed edward taber at the investment management firm of t rowe 
price associates in his forecast for 1991 the less obvious 
factor which could alter our forecast is a much stronger economy 
than is currently in the consensus 
that could occur taber contends as a result of such forces as 
the feds easing heavy deficit spending by the government tight 
inventories at many businesses and any revival of consumer 
spending 
should this alternative become reality we would expect rates 
to move markedly higher throughout the year he said 
the stock market struggled with such doubts through the past 
week changing directions at least half a dozen times the dow 
jones average of 30 industrials closed friday at 259381 up 371 
from the week before 
the new york stock exchange composite index dropped 36 to 
17871 the american stock exchange market value index fell 71 to 
30574 and the nasdaq composite index for the overthecounter 
market was down 271 at 36883 
volume on the big board averaged 15585 million shares a day 
against 200 million in the previous week 
wary analysts recall that interestrate hopes also ran high last 
year about this time the dow jones industrial average reached a 
thenrecord closing peak of 281015 last jan 2 
but it tumbled 26691 points or 95 percent over the next four 
weeks as rates unexpectedly turned higher following the lead of 
interest rates in japan and germany 
if rates keep declining now some observers say they could be 
signaling a deeperthanexpected recession chilling any joy over 
cheaper money 
with all this though many optimists remain on wall street 
offering assurances that the economy and the markets can ride out 
the storm 
will lower interest rates revive economic growth they always 
have in the past said edward yardeni chief economist at 
prudentialbache securities 
interest rates should hit their lows around march if the 
economy starts to show some signs of life during the first quarter 
as we expect 
if however the economy continues to fall during the first 
quarter then interest rates will fall as low as necessary to 
revive economic growth 
