reorganization options 
southland filed for chapter 11 reorganization in october with a 
prepackaged plan already approved by most of its creditors 
us bankruptcy judge harold abramson must confirm the plan for it 
to take effect 
abramson said he would first hear arguments over southlands 
attempts to inform creditors of the dallasbased companys 
financial condition and options then hear arguments on the merits 
of the reorganization plan the hearing is expected to last for 
several weeks 
at the time of the bankruptcy filing southland listed 253 
billion in assets and 338 billion in liabilities and said it was 
overwhelmed by debt left from its 49 billion debtfinanced 
takeover in 1987 
during opening statements attorneys for creditors who oppose 
the plan argued that southland did not give them enough time for 
its consideration used a complicated ballot and withheld 
information about the compensation of the companys founding 
family 
southlands attorney mike sutherland of dallas said the 
company followed existing regulations for a prepackaged filing he 
said the dissenting creditors want abramson to give them more 
leverage than they have 
southland is the largest of a handful of companies to try a 
prepackaged filing first used about a year ago the companys case 
has drawn extraordinary attention in the legal community because of 
its precedentsetting use of the prepackaging 
proponents of the prepackaging device say it reduces the time a 
company stays in bankruptcy and assures a fairer deal for a greater 
number of creditors 
ordinarily a company presents a reorganization plan months or 
even years later after filing for bankruptcy and creditors often 
challenge it often a small number of creditors called holdouts 
will vote against any reorganization in hopes of a separate deal 
that is better leaving the majority to accept repayment on terms 
that arent as good 
when a judge approves a prepackaged filing its terms are 
imposed on all creditors 
peter wolfson attorney for some of the dissenting creditors 
said the company doesnt have the support for the plan that it has 
portrayed but he acknowledged that in most aspects the companys 
plan is supported by a majority of the people that southland owes 
money 
under the plan creditors end up with control of 25 percent of 
the company southlands japanese affiliates itoyokado co ltd 
and seveneleven japan co ltd get 70 percent and the rest is 
left to the the companys founders the thompson family of dallas 
jere and john thompson sons of southland founder joe thompson 
lose their posts as the companys chief officers they remain 
directors and continue to be paid 600000 annually under the 
plan their brother joe thompson jr would also remain a director 
of southland 
abramson began the hearing by refusing to give another 45 days 
for the securities and exchange commission to review the southland 
plan 
sec attorney john lee said agency officials wanted the extension 
because southlands plan would set a precedent for other 
prepackaged bankruptcy cases 
abramson said the extension was too long for an opinion that is 
not required by the bankruptcy code the judge asked the sec to 
present a statement of position to help him form a ruling 
if the commission could make some kind of statement by dec 
31st or the first week of january that would be helpful to the 
court abramson said otherwise ill excuse you from that 
request 
the buck stops here anyway abramson said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

