<TEXT>
charles keating jrs insurance companies should 
be required to pay part of any courtordered damages arising from 
the collapse of keatings financial empire a classaction lawsuit 
contends 
the suit was filed in us district court by the federal 
government and investors in keatings phoenixbased american 
continental corp it contends that 21 insurance companies are 
liable for as much as 110 million 
the policies impose an obligation on the respective insurance 
company defendants to provide insurance coverage for the acts of 
the insured defendants that caused damage and losses to the 
plaintiffs the lawsuit says 
the suit asks that the court to determine immediately the 
scope and amount of coverage the policies provide 
the suit was filed by four investors and the resolution trust 
corp the federal agency empowered to dispose of the assets of 
failed savings and loans it was brought on behalf of more than 
20000 people who bought american continental junk bonds through 
lincoln savings and loan association keatings californiabased 
thrift 
federal regulators seized lincoln savings in april 1989 one day 
after american continental and 11 of the thrifts subsidiaries 
filed for protection under chapter 11 of the us bankruptcy code 
keating members of his family and his former top executives are 
defendants in lawsuits filed by the government and investors 
seeking more than 13 billion in damages 
the federal government is seeking 11 billion in a fraud and 
racketeering suit that blames keating and his associates for the 
failure of lincoln savings 
in a separate suit more than 17000 investors who put about 
200 million into american continental securities are demanding 
their money back 
the 21 insurance companies named as defendants in the 
classaction suit filed thursday sold policies covering actions 
taken by keating and his executives that can be tied to the 
collapse of american continental and lincoln savings according to 
the suit 
the insurance companies contend that some of the policies are 
self consuming which means the proceeds are being used to pay 
the legal bills run up by keating and the others in various civil 
suits 
the lawsuit argues however that policy provisions that allow 
deductions for legal fees are vague ambiguous and unenforceable 
as a result of this dispute proceeds of certain policies are 
wasting and elderly plaintiffs are losing their rights to certain 
recoveries the lawsuit says unless this court determines the 
rights and obligations of the parties many of the insurance 
policies may be wasted or diminished to zero 
a federal judge last may ordered national union fire insurance 
co of pittsburgh one of the insurance companies to pay for legal 
bills of keating and his associates under two of its policies 
the investors requested each insurer last may to deposit the 
amount of the policies into interestbearing accounts to pay any 
courtawarded damages but the companies have been reluctant to do 
so the suit contends 
the suit was assigned to judge richard bilby and probably will 
be consolidated with other pending keating suits according to the 
court clerks office 
